<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="210" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,541,1233,1259]" box="[151,541,1233,1259]" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,541,1233,1259]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,541,1233,1259]" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perez in Tkalcu" authorityYear="1975" box="[151,366,1233,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uncicornis">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,366,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Osmia uncicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1305,1583]" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">
The species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perez in Tkalcu" authorityYear="1975" box="[364,517,1305,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uncicornis">
<emphasis box="[364,517,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">O. uncicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group differ from those of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Morawitz" authorityYear="1875" box="[957,1084,1305,1331]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis box="[957,1084,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">O. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group in both sexes by the foxy red tergal pilosity (whitish or yellowish in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perez" authorityYear="1879" box="[723,885,1341,1367]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argyropyga">
<emphasis box="[723,885,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">O. argyropyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in the female sex by the lack of clubbed bristles on the fore tarsus and in the male sex by the following strongly derived characters: antennal flagellum distinctly crenulate, ventral side of middle femur with median keel-like projection, middle tibia swollen and curved, tergum 6 four-toothed and mediobasally with polished longitudinal keel or bulge (
<figureCitation box="[986,1082,1448,1476]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[195,1391,775,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[195,1391,775,1917]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–7: Osmia (Hemiosmia). 1: Female of O. balearica on Lotus creticus (Fabaceae; photo V. Haeseler). 2: Female of O. uncicornis digging out nest burrow in loose soil (photo V. Haeseler). 3: Excavated brood cells of O. uncicornis. 4: Copulating pair of O. balearica (photo V. Haeseler). 5–7: Male terga 5–6 of O. uncicornis (5), O. argyropyga (6) and O. difficilis (7)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3826172" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3826172/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Fig. 5, 6</figureCitation>
), tergum 7 with narrow median projection possessing a straight to emarginate apical margin, sternum 4 medioapically densely covered with hooked bristles and prolonged into a triangular projection, sternum 5 with deep median incision, sternum 6 apically beset with curved bristles and apex of gonoforceps bifid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
